To create a chessboard diagram in LaTeX using the `pic` package and the `chessboard` library, follow these steps:

1. Install the `chessboard` package by running `usepackage(chessboard)`.
2. Add the `pic` package to include graphics.
3. Create a new macro named `\MyChessboard` to define the chessboard diagram.
4. Include the `\MyChessboard` macro in your LaTeX document.

Here's the complete code:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\makeatletter
\newcommand{\MyChessboard}[1]{%
  \begin{picture}(15,15)%
    \chessboard[fen=#1]{a}{r}
    \put(4,4){White King}
    \put(12,4){Black King}
  \end{picture}%
}
\makeatother

\begin{document}

\MyChessboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}% FEN notation for a standard starting position

\end{document}
```

Replace "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1" with your desired FEN notation. This code will generate a chessboard diagram based on the given FEN notation, with optional annotations for White and Black kings. The `graphicx` package is not required, but if you want to adjust the size or position of the board, you can use its features.

