In Java, the "==" operator is used for primitive types and object comparison, while the ".equals()" method is used for comparing the contents of two strings. 

The "==" operator performs a reference comparison, which means it compares whether the two objects are the same in memory. If you use this operator to compare strings, it will compare the memory addresses of the two strings, not their actual content. This is where the bug in your program came from.

On the other hand, the ".equals()" method compares the contents of the two strings. It checks whether the characters in both strings are in the same order and have the same values. If you use this method to compare strings, it will work correctly even if the strings are not the same object in memory.

Here's a simple example:

```java
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "World";

if (str1 == str2) {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are the same");
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are different");
}

if (str1.equals(str2)) {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 have the same content");
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 have different content");
}
```

In this example, the first comparison using "==" returns false, as they are not the same object in memory. However, the second comparison using ".equals()" returns true, as they have the same content.

In summary, always use the ".equals()" method to compare strings in Java instead of the "==" operator. The "==" operator performs a reference comparison, while the ".equals()" method compares the contents of the strings. This ensures that your code behaves correctly, even if two strings with different content appear to be the same object in memory.

To find the CSS code for a light red color with a medium light shade of pink, you can use the `color` property with the `rgb()` function to define the specific shade. Here's an example of the CSS code you could use:

```css
.light-red-pink {
  --light-red: rgb(255, 0, 80);
  --medium-light-pink: rgb(255, 127, 141);

  color: linear-gradient(to bottom, var(--light-red), var(--medium-light-pink));
}
```

In this code, we first define two variables: `--light-red` and `--medium-light-pink`. The `--light-red` variable is set to an RGB value representing a light red color, and `--medium-light-pink` is set to an RGB value representing a medium light shade of pink.

Next, we create a gradient background for the color using these variables. The `linear-gradient` function is used to create a smooth transition from one color to another (in this case, from `--light-red` to `--medium-light-pink`). The `to bottom` direction ensures that the colors appear in the correct order when the text is scrolled.

Finally, we apply this gradient color to the `color` property of an element using the `var()` function. This function takes a value and returns its corresponding CSS property (in this case, the `--light-red` variable for the `color` property).

Remember to replace `.light-red-pink` with the actual class or ID of the element you want to apply this style to.

Please note that this example uses CSS gradients, which may not be supported in older browsers. For cross-browser compatibility, consider using a library like `fabric.js` or `css-gradients` to add support for CSS gradients.

